[
    {
        "content": "<p>I am explicitly not going to give Lean code here, because I want to know how you would write it in Lean. I am looking for the following mathematical statement: If <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>V</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">V</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">V</span></span></span></span> is a (finite dimensional if you want) <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\R</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span></span></span></span>-vector space and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Δ</mi><mo>⊆</mo><mi>V</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Delta \\subseteq V</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8193em;vertical-align:-0.136em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Δ</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⊆</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">V</span></span></span></span> is a finite set, then <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">{</mo><mi>f</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>V</mi><mo>→</mo><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi><mo>∣</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∀</mi><mi>d</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Δ</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>f</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>d</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">}</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\{f : V \\to \\R \\mid \\forall d \\in \\Delta, f(d) = 0\\}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">{</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">V</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∣</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7335em;vertical-align:-0.0391em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∀</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">d</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∈</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Δ</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">d</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mclose\">}</span></span></span></span> has codimension at most <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∣</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Δ</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∣</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">|\\Delta|</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∣Δ∣</span></span></span></span> as a subspace of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>V</mi><mo>→</mo><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">V \\to \\R</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">V</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span></span></span></span> (the space of linear maps, not just bare functions).</p>",
        "id": 468716128,
        "sender_full_name": "Yaël Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1725870183
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Do we have this, in any form?</p>",
        "id": 468716162,
        "sender_full_name": "Yaël Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1725870196
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If <code>W</code> is the subspace spanned by <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Δ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Delta</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Δ</span></span></span></span> (<code>Submodule.span \\R \\Delta</code>), then your set is <code>W.dualAnnihilator</code>, and the codimension of it can be calculated using <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=Subspace.quotAnnihilatorEquiv#doc\">docs#Subspace.quotAnnihilatorEquiv</a> to see that <code>Dual \\R V / W.dualAnnihilator</code> is <code>Dual \\R W</code>, which has dimension at most <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∣</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Δ</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∣</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">|\\Delta|</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∣Δ∣</span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 468722960,
        "sender_full_name": "Kyle Miller",
        "timestamp": 1725871925
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Nice! Do we have any spelling for codimension but <code>finrank k Space - finrank k Subspace</code>?</p>",
        "id": 468735668,
        "sender_full_name": "Yaël Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1725874722
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It looks like <code>Module.rank k (Space / Subspace)</code> is common for codimension. Given that there's no <code>corank</code> or <code>codim</code>, I'd probably put theorems into that form. This has the benefit that it supports infinite dimensional subspaces of finite codimension.</p>",
        "id": 468870827,
        "sender_full_name": "Kyle Miller",
        "timestamp": 1725903340
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Okay, that's a nice suggestion! I will adapt to it</p>",
        "id": 468877655,
        "sender_full_name": "Yaël Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1725905433
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Do we then have antitonicity of codimension with this spelling?</p>",
        "id": 468877831,
        "sender_full_name": "Yaël Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1725905497
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm sure there's something for antitonicity of quotients, but for codimension itself the only things I can find are <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=Submodule.finrank_quotient_add_finrank#doc\">docs#Submodule.finrank_quotient_add_finrank</a> and <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=rank_quotient_add_rank#doc\">docs#rank_quotient_add_rank</a></p>",
        "id": 468880684,
        "sender_full_name": "Kyle Miller",
        "timestamp": 1725906341
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"306601\">Kyle Miller</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/217875-Is-there-code-for-X.3F/topic/Codimension.20of.20the.20annihilator/near/468870827\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>It looks like <code>Module.rank k (Space / Subspace)</code> is common for codimension. Given that there's no <code>corank</code> or <code>codim</code>, I'd probably put theorems into that form. This has the benefit that it supports infinite dimensional subspaces of finite codimension.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Nevertheless, we should probably turn this into a defn, and write a little API for it. Don't you think?</p>",
        "id": 468994928,
        "sender_full_name": "Johan Commelin",
        "timestamp": 1725949281
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Should it be a particular case of a more general theory for modules of finite length?</p>",
        "id": 469003423,
        "sender_full_name": "Antoine Chambert-Loir",
        "timestamp": 1725951988
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You mean that we should generalize <code>k</code>? I agree.</p>",
        "id": 469003705,
        "sender_full_name": "Johan Commelin",
        "timestamp": 1725952070
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>On the other hand, “le mieux est l'ennemi du bien” as we say in French, so maybe it's better to have today some API which is not fully general, but can be generalized by somebody who needs it — and builds on it — than never having the ultimate one.</p>",
        "id": 469004526,
        "sender_full_name": "Antoine Chambert-Loir",
        "timestamp": 1725952263
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"130609\">Antoine Chambert-Loir</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/217875-Is-there-code-for-X.3F/topic/Codimension.20of.20the.20annihilator/near/469004526\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>On the other hand, “le mieux est l'ennemi du bien” as we say in French, so maybe it's better to have today some API which is not fully general, but can be generalized by somebody who needs it — and builds on it — than never having the ultimate one.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>(as an aside: I've also heard this phrase in English so I was curious about its origin, supposedly it's originally an Italian proverb!)</p>",
        "id": 469030489,
        "sender_full_name": "Bhavik Mehta",
        "timestamp": 1725957930
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Which one?</p>",
        "id": 469033940,
        "sender_full_name": "Riccardo Brasca",
        "timestamp": 1725958851
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"130609\">Antoine Chambert-Loir</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/217875-Is-there-code-for-X.3F/topic/Codimension.20of.20the.20annihilator/near/469003423\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Should it be a particular case of a more general theory for modules of finite length?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I don't know what a module of finite length is. Can you expand on what the generalisation would look like?</p>",
        "id": 469036790,
        "sender_full_name": "Yaël Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1725959613
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(finite length means there's a finite chain of submodules such that each one when quotiented out by the next one is a simple module, i.e. only has bot and top as submodules. For example you would filter a f.d.v.s over <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">k</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03148em;\">k</span></span></span></span> by subspaces with dimensions growing by 1 each time, as the simple <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">k</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03148em;\">k</span></span></span></span>-modules are the 1d ones if <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">k</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03148em;\">k</span></span></span></span> is a field. The finite length <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Z</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{Z}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Z</span></span></span></span>-modules (i.e. abelian groups) are precisely the finite ones.)</p>",
        "id": 469083329,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1725973056
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Indeed. (That's gives a slightly different point of view on dimension on vector spaces — rather than looking at bases, look at flags, increasing systems of subspaces <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>V</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>⊂</mo><msub><mi>V</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>⊂</mo><mo>⋯</mo><mo>⊂</mo><msub><mi>V</mi><mi>m</mi></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> V_0\\subset V_1\\subset\\dots\\subset V_m </annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">V</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3011em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.2222em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">0</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⊂</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">V</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3011em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.2222em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⊂</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.5782em;vertical-align:-0.0391em;\"></span><span class=\"minner\">⋯</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⊂</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">V</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.1514em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.2222em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">m</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>, such that all inclusions are strict and can't be refined.)</p>",
        "id": 469109753,
        "sender_full_name": "Antoine Chambert-Loir",
        "timestamp": 1725978621
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"130609\">Antoine Chambert-Loir</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/217875-Is-there-code-for-X.3F/topic/Codimension.20of.20the.20annihilator/near/469003423\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Should it be a particular case of a more general theory for modules of finite length?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>That would only be for finite corank, correct? The <code>Module.rank k (Mod / SubMod)</code> definition works for infinite corank as well.</p>\n<p>It seems to me that the theory of <code>Module.rank k (Mod / SubMod)</code> should be related to the theory of modules of finite length in situations where it can be done, but in general these seem to be different.</p>",
        "id": 469129229,
        "sender_full_name": "Kyle Miller",
        "timestamp": 1725981976
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>if dimension is length or height, codimension is colength or coheight, with a similar API which, btw, should already be implemented in a way or another.</p>",
        "id": 469130509,
        "sender_full_name": "Antoine Chambert-Loir",
        "timestamp": 1725982351
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Would this be restricting dimensions to <em>finite</em> dimensions though? Or would the definition of a flag be generalized to be a chain of submodules?</p>",
        "id": 469131251,
        "sender_full_name": "Kyle Miller",
        "timestamp": 1725982544
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>A flag is a chain of submodules, the length of a module is the supremum of the lengths of all chains (<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>V</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>⊂</mo><mo>⋯</mo><mo>⊂</mo><msub><mi>V</mi><mi>m</mi></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> V_0\\subset \\dots \\subset V_m </annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">V</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3011em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.2222em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">0</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⊂</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.5782em;vertical-align:-0.0391em;\"></span><span class=\"minner\">⋯</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⊂</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">V</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.1514em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.2222em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">m</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> has length <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>m</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">m</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">m</span></span></span></span>), the height and the coheight of a submodule are the supremum of the lengths of all chains ending or starting (I'm not clear about which is which) at this submodule.</p>",
        "id": 469136147,
        "sender_full_name": "Antoine Chambert-Loir",
        "timestamp": 1725983567
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>One has height + coheight = length, with usual conventions for infinite addition.</p>",
        "id": 469136702,
        "sender_full_name": "Antoine Chambert-Loir",
        "timestamp": 1725983635
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Just to be clear, the definition of \"chain of submodules\" I'm using is \"a totally ordered subset of submodules\". The definition of flag I'm familiar with are the ones indexed by some set <code>{0,1,...,m}</code>. With flags, the only possible lengths are <code>0,1,2,...,\\infty</code>, but with chains you can have any cardinality.</p>",
        "id": 469168842,
        "sender_full_name": "Kyle Miller",
        "timestamp": 1725990607
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Just noting that <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"470149\">@Joachim Breitner</span> is currently doing very good work on redefining the notion of (co)height of an element in an order</p>",
        "id": 469216146,
        "sender_full_name": "Yaël Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1726003060
    },
    {
